<ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">speaker</ENAMEX>. Most of the time, in my experience, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bradley</ENAMEX> comes across more
eloquently on the printed page that in his own speaking voice, which has all
the effervescence of <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">day-old champagne</ENAMEX>. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Today</TIMEX> it seemed just the reverse.
Comments that might read as platitudinous rang with quiet <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">force</ENAMEX> and sincerity.
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bradley</ENAMEX> spoke for <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">nearly 45 minutes</TIMEX> and held the attention of a large, mostly
conservative <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">audience</ENAMEX> throughout with a mixture of gentle humor, anecdote, and
explicit policy talk. Of course, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bradley</ENAMEX> has always been the opposite of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gore</ENAMEX>
